full_text:
@AnaMardoll my reaction was so extreme that there was therapy involved (my therapist is a miracle worker can i just say) and I think it colors my ability to process authors getting treated as outsiders when they aren't.

Also, someone being in the community doesn't mean immune from criticism
full_text(utf-8): b"@AnaMardoll my reaction was so extreme that there was therapy involved (my therapist is a miracle worker can i just say) and I think it colors my ability to process authors getting treated as outsiders when they aren't.\n\nAlso, someone being in the community doesn't mean immune from criticism"

b"@AnaMardoll like, you have the right to feel all the ways you feel about this, too.

I've just never been closeted as a writer and still got treated as an outsider, even though it was a small minority of readers.

some of the reactions to bisexuality are really bizarre."

b"@AnaMardoll and the plot twist part of that is, I wasn't closeted or even in a relationship that looked like m/f to the outside world at the time. This was when my ex was still presenting female and not out. Some people are just that o_O at bi women.

it was stressful.

(2/2)"

b'@AnaMardoll I have complicated feelings about this that I KNOW are way more about my own trauma history than they are about today\'s author.\nbc the "strangers attributing the stuff you wrote about your own life in your book, to you being bigoted" has happened to me\n(1/2)'
